{"title_page": "Kapurthala State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox Former Subdivision\n|conventional_long_name = Kapurthala State\n|common_name = Kapurthala\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = New Imperialism\n|year_start = 1772\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1947\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 = Sikh Confederacy\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 =Kattar Dhal Talwar.jpg\n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Kapurthala flag.svg\n|image_coat = Coat of arms of Kapurthala State.jpg\n|image_map = Punjab 1909.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Kapurthala State on a 1909 [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]] map.\n|stat_area1 =352\n|stat_year1 = 1901\n|stat_pop1 = 314,341\n|today     = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]] \n|footnotes = [http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V14_414.gif Kapurthala state] [[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]], 1909, v. 14, ''p.&nbsp;408\u2013416''.\n}}\n[[File:Fateh Singh Ahluwalia.png|thumb|Raja Fateh Singh Ahluwalia, [[Companion of Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]] ]]\n[[File:Major-General H.H. Farzand-i-Dilband Rasikh- al-Iqtidad-i-Daulat-i-Inglishia, Raja-i-Rajagan, Maharaja Sir Jagatjit Singh, Bahadur, Maharaja of Kapurthala, GCSI , GCIE , GBE.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Jagatjit Singh]] Bahadur, Maharaja of Kapurthala, [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]], [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire|GBE]].]]\n'''Kapurthala State''', with its capital at [[Kapurthala]], was a former [[Princely state]] of [[Punjab region|Punjab]], Ruled by [[Ahluwalia (misl)|Ahluwalia]] [[Sikh]] rulers, spread across {{convert|352|sqmi|km2}}. According to the 1901 census the state had a population of 314,341 and contained two towns and 167 villages.<ref name=\"imp\">[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V14_414.gif Kapurthala state] ''[[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]]'', 1909, v. 14, p. 408.</ref> In 1930, Kapurthala became part of the [[Punjab States Agency]] and acceded to the [[Dominion of India|Union of India]] in 1947.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe ruling dynasty of Kapurthala originated in the [[Ahluwalia (misl)|Ahluwalia]] [[misl]]. The dynasty's records trace their ancestry to the Bhatti tribe of [[Jaisalmer State|Jaisalmer]]. After 1530 they are called Bhatti, and ultimately, the Hindu deity [[Krishna]]. According to this account, Krishna's descendant Gaj built the fort of [[Ghazni|Gajni]], and lost his life in a battle against a joint [[Roman Empire|Roman]]-[[Greater Khorasan|Khorasani]] army. His son [[Shalivahana|Salibahan]] established the city of [[Sialkot]], and started the [[Shaka era|Shak era]] after defeating the [[Shakas|Shaks]] in 78 CE. After the Muslim conquest of Punjab, his descendants migrated to the [[Jaisalmer State|Jaisalmer]] area, where they came to be known as Bhatti tribe. After [[Alauddin Khalji]]'s conquest of Jaisalmer, some of the Bhatti tribe people's migrated to [[Tarn Taran district]], mingled with [[Jats]]. Gradually, they came to be known as Jats, and in the 17th century, they joined [[Guru Hargobind]]'s army. Ganda Singh of this family raided [[Lahore]], whose governor Dilawar Khan persuaded him to join the Lahore army, and assigned him the [[jagir|fief]] of Ahlu and some other villages. Ganda Singh's son Sadhu (or Sadho) Singh lived in Ahlu, because of which the family came to be known as Ahluwalia. Sadhu Singh and his four sons married into Kalal families, because of which the family came to be known as Ahluwalia. The descendants of Sadhu Singh son Gopal Singh (who was the grandfather of Jassa Singh) established the royal family of Kapurthala.<ref name=\"Ganda_1990\">{{cite book |author=Ganda Singh |title=Sardar Jassa Singh Ahluwalia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f4ZHAAAAMAAJ |year=1990 |publisher=Punjabi University |pages=1\u20134 }}</ref>\n\nThe British administrator [[Lepel Griffin]] (1873) dismissed this account as spurious.<ref name=\"Ganda_1990\"/> The Sikh author Gian Singh, in his ''Twarikh Raj Khalsa'' (1894), wrote that the Ahluwalia family adopted the Kalal caste identity much before Sadhu Singh.<ref>{{cite book |author=M. L. Ahluwalia|title=Land marks in Sikh history |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1DduAAAAMAAJ |year=1996 |publisher=Ashoka International |page=37 }}</ref>\n\nThe Ahluwalia misl rose to prominence under [[Jassa Singh Ahluwalia]],<ref name=\"KR_2015\">{{cite book |title=Military Manpower, Armies and Warfare in South Asia |author=Kaushik Roy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GpNECgAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=9781317321279 |page=88 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last =Singhia |first=H.S. |title=The encyclopedia of Sikhism |publisher=Hemkunt Press |year=2009 |location=New Delhi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C&pg=PA111 |isbn=978-81-7010-301-1 |page=111}}</ref> who is regarded as the founder of the Kapurthala State.<ref>{{cite book |author=Sohan Singh Seetal |title=The Sikh Misals and the Punjab States |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KD4uAAAAMAAJ |year=1981 |publisher=Lahore Book Shop |page=75 }}</ref>\n\n==Royal family==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Sardars===\n* [[Jassa Singh Ahluwalia|Jassa Singh]] (1777 \u2013 20 October 1783)<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/k/kapurthala.html Kapurthala]</ref> (b. 1718 \u2013 d. 1783)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.royalfamilyofindia.com/kapurthala/|title=KAPURTHALA|date=2013-04-12|work=Royal Family of India|access-date=2018-01-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[Bagh Singh of Kapurthala|Bagh Singh]] (20 October 1783 \u2013 10 July 1801) (b. 1747 \u2013 d. 1801)<ref>[https://www.royalark.net/India/kapurth2.htm Royal Ark]</ref>\n\n===Rajas===\n*[[Fateh Singh of Kapurthala|Fateh Singh]] (10 July 1801 \u2013 20 October 1837) (b. 1784 \u2013 d. 1837)\n* [[Nihal Singh of Kapurthala|Nihal Singh]] (20 October 1837 \u2013 13 September 1852) (b. 1817 \u2013 d. 1852)\n* [[Randhir Singh of Kapurthala|Randhir Singh]] (13 September 1852 \u2013 12 March 1861) (b. 1831 \u2013 d. 1870)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Raja-i Rajgan===\n* [[Randhir Singh of Kapurthala|Randhir Singh]] (12 March 1861 \u2013 2 April 1870) (b. 1831 \u2013 d. 1870)\n* [[Kharak Singh of Kapurthala|Kharak Singh]] (2 April 1870 \u2013  3 September 1877) (b. 1850 \u2013 d. 1877)\n* [[Jagatjit Singh]] (3 September 1877 \u2013 12 December 1911) (b. 1872 \u2013 d. 1949)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Maharajas===\n* [[Jagatjit Singh]] (12 December 1911 \u2013 15 August 1947) (b. 1872 \u2013 d. 1949)<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Paramjit Singh\n*Sukhjit Singh\n\n==See also==\n*[[Anita Delgado]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n*[http://www.royalark.net/India/kapurth.htm Kapurthala History and detailed Genealogy] Royalark\n*[http://www.sikh-heritage.co.uk/heritage/Maharajas%20of%20Punjab/kapurthala/kapurthala.htm Kapurthala] www.sikh-heritage.co.uk\n\n{{Princely states of India}}\n{{Princely states of the Punjab and Simla Hills}}\n{{coord|31|23|N|75|23|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kapurthala State|Kapurthala State]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox Former Subdivision\n|conventional_long_name = Kapurthala State\n|common_name = Kapurthala\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = New Imperialism\n|year_start = 1772\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1947\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 = Sikh Confederacy\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 =Kattar Dhal Talwar.jpg\n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Kapurthala flag.svg\n|image_coat = Coat of arms of Kapurthala State.jpg\n|image_map = Punjab 1909.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Kapurthala State on a 1909 [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]] map.\n|stat_area1 =352\n|stat_year1 = 1901\n|stat_pop1 = 314,341\n|today     = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]] \n|footnotes = [http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V14_414.gif Kapurthala state] [[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]], 1909, v. 14, ''p.&nbsp;408\u2013416''.\n}}\n[[File:Fateh Singh Ahluwalia.png|thumb|Raja Fateh Singh Ahluwalia, [[Companion of Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]] ]]\n[[File:Major-General H.H. Farzand-i-Dilband Rasikh- al-Iqtidad-i-Daulat-i-Inglishia, Raja-i-Rajagan, Maharaja Sir Jagatjit Singh, Bahadur, Maharaja of Kapurthala, GCSI , GCIE , GBE.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Jagatjit Singh]] Bahadur, Maharaja of Kapurthala, [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]], [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire|GBE]].]]\n'''Kapurthala State''', with its capital at [[Kapurthala]], was a former [[Princely state]] of [[Punjab region|Punjab]], Ruled by [[Ahluwalia (misl)|Ahluwalia]] [[Sikh]] rulers, spread across {{convert|352|sqmi|km2}}. According to the 1901 census the state had a population of 314,341 and contained two towns and 167 villages.<ref name=\"imp\">[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V14_414.gif Kapurthala state] ''[[The Imperial Gazetteer of India]]'', 1909, v. 14, p. 408.</ref> In 1930, Kapurthala became part of the [[Punjab States Agency]] and acceded to the [[Union of India]] in 1947.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe ruling dynasty of Kapurthala originated in the [[Ahluwalia (misl)|Ahluwalia]] [[misl]]. The dynasty's records trace their ancestry to the Bhatti tribe of [[Jaisalmer State|Jaisalmer]]. After 1530 they are called Bhatti, and ultimately, the Hindu deity [[Krishna]]. According to this account, Krishna's descendant Gaj built the fort of [[Ghazni|Gajni]], and lost